<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">I am a ranger myself (amongst other things) and have spent much time in CT. Sorry, but I will have to mostly disagree with you. Why should anyone in a pick-up group have to give up their chance at getting more money simply because you dont have that item yet? If they already won a good item in that pick-up group that they are in, than yes they should be excluded, but other than that (and when its a quest item they cant even use or profit from), all items should be fair game to whomever in the group wants in. At the higher levels things are done differently mostley (in my case) because we all know each other and arnt really in a pick-up group full of strangers mainly there for  their own purpose. At level 50, people go to the planes and this is where if you need it and it drops you get it or get to random with all the class for that item that needs it. Reason is, all the stuff is lore and no drop (read: cant trade cant sell) and no one but that class can even equip it. If you were lvl 50 fighting in a pick-up group and tradable items drops, guess what.....everyone will want in on the random whether they can use it (on this character) or not. You can always trade it for items you do need or sell it to buy items you do need. Dont tell me you never hear lvl50 + wizards auctioning off lvl50+ warrior gear or lvl50+ warriors auctioning off lvl50+ caster gear.<br>
     Lets say you make it so no casters can be involved in a random for the gear that drops in CT simply because they cant use it. Can you guess what would happen? <br>
    CT would be very underpopulated in casters. They are taking the same risk as you, so why should they be excluded from the occasional nuggets of wealth that pops up? All items have a money value and everyone can use money.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="CENTER">
