<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5" align="CENTER">
<tr>
<td valign="MIDDLE"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="000000">HMMM, this is a sticky point.<p>

I will give my opinion, but I think it will all come down to who you are grouping with and thier attitudes.<p>

Personally, I do not roll for anything I can not use unless there is NO ONE in the group who can use it.  I also pass on rolls when I finally do get something I can use, so that someone else gets a chance at it.<p>

I have seen people state the rules as follows (but again, you have to be working with people that WANT to play this way, you can NOT force your style of play on anyone, even if you think it is the fairest way to play).<p>

1. Everyone who can USE the item rolls for it provided they have not already gotten an item<br>
  (I have even gone so far as to not roll for an item I really wanted as a warrior just because a pure caster probably needed it more)<br>
2. If no one can use the item, everyone who has not gotten an item rolls for it<p>

<br>
So, again, just pick who you play with - if you are in a guild, ask your guild leader to establish some rules IF the group is all guild members.  For example, people in my guild were rolling for items if thier TWINK could use them, and we generally agreed as a guild that the character must be in the group to count for the number 1 rule, hehe.<p>

Remember, you can always say PASS when the rolling comes around so you can stick with your principles.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr bgcolor="DDDDDD">
